<Layout title="Post Market Surveillance">

<Navbar />

<section class="hero">

<div class="container">

<span class="badge">
EU MDR • ISO 13485 • PMS
</span>

<h1>Post Market Surveillance (PMS)</h1>

<p>

Post Market Surveillance (PMS) is a proactive and systematic process
used by medical device manufacturers to continuously collect, review,
analyze and act on information obtained after a device has been placed
on the market.

The objective is to ensure continued safety, performance and regulatory
compliance throughout the product life cycle.

</p>

<div class="buttons">

<a href="/learn/clinical-evaluation" class="secondary">
← Previous
</a>

<a href="/iso/iso-13485" class="primary">
Next →
</a>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>What is Post Market Surveillance?</h2>

<p>

Post Market Surveillance is a continuous process performed after product
commercialization to monitor real-world performance, identify new risks,
detect trends and implement corrective actions whenever necessary.

PMS supports continuous improvement and provides evidence that the
benefits of the medical device continue to outweigh the risks.

</p>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Objectives of PMS</h2>

<div class="grid">

<div class="card">

<h3>Patient Safety</h3>

<p>

Identify safety issues before they become widespread.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Performance Monitoring</h3>

<p>

Confirm that the device continues to perform as intended.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Regulatory Compliance</h3>

<p>

Meet EU MDR, ISO 13485 and national regulatory requirements.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Continuous Improvement</h3>

<p>

Use field data to improve products and manufacturing processes.

</p>

</div>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Sources of PMS Data</h2>

<table>

<tr>
<th>Source</th>
<th>Description</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Customer Complaints</td>
<td>Feedback received from users and hospitals.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Adverse Events</td>
<td>Serious incidents reported during product use.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Scientific Literature</td>
<td>Published papers and case reports.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Clinical Follow-up (PMCF)</td>
<td>Long-term clinical performance data.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Regulatory Databases</td>
<td>FDA MAUDE, CDSCO, TGA, Health Canada, EUDAMED (where applicable).</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Distributor Feedback</td>
<td>Information from dealers and distributors.</td>
</tr>

</table>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>PMS Process Flow</h2>

<div class="timeline">

<div class="step">Collect Data</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">Analyze Trends</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">Risk Evaluation</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">CAPA</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">Update RMF & CER</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">Regulatory Reporting</div>

<div class="arrow">→</div>

<div class="step">Continuous Monitoring</div>

</div>

</div>

</section>
<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Complaint Handling</h2>

<p>

Complaint Handling is a structured process used to receive, document,
investigate and resolve customer complaints related to medical devices.
Each complaint should be evaluated to determine whether it indicates a
trend, safety issue or reportable adverse event.

</p>

<table>

<tr>
<th>Step</th>
<th>Description</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Complaint Receipt</td>
<td>Receive complaint from customer, distributor or hospital.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Complaint Registration</td>
<td>Assign Complaint ID and document all available information.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Investigation</td>
<td>Determine root cause using technical and quality evidence.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Risk Assessment</td>
<td>Evaluate patient risk using ISO 14971 principles.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>CAPA</td>
<td>Implement corrective and preventive actions if required.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Closure</td>
<td>Document conclusions and verify effectiveness.</td>
</tr>

</table>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Vigilance Reporting</h2>

<p>

Vigilance Reporting is the regulatory reporting of serious incidents and
Field Safety Corrective Actions (FSCA) to competent authorities.

The purpose is to ensure rapid communication of safety issues and
protect patients from recurring incidents.

</p>

<div class="grid">

<div class="card">

<h3>Reportable Events</h3>

<ul>

<li>Death</li>

<li>Serious Injury</li>

<li>Device Malfunction</li>

<li>Incorrect Labelling</li>

<li>Sterility Failure</li>

<li>Software Failure</li>

</ul>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Authorities</h3>

<ul>

<li>CDSCO (India)</li>

<li>US FDA</li>

<li>Health Canada</li>

<li>TGA Australia</li>

<li>EU Competent Authorities</li>

</ul>

</div>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Trend Analysis</h2>

<p>

Manufacturers should continuously monitor complaint data to identify
unexpected increases in failure rates or recurring issues.

Trend analysis helps detect problems before they become major safety
events.

</p>

<table>

<tr>
<th>Trend</th>
<th>Action</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Increase in complaints</td>
<td>Perform investigation and risk assessment.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Repeated failures</td>
<td>Initiate CAPA.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Safety concern</td>
<td>Evaluate need for Vigilance Reporting.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Design issue</td>
<td>Update Design Documentation and RMF.</td>
</tr>

</table>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Periodic Safety Update Report (PSUR)</h2>

<p>

The PSUR summarizes Post Market Surveillance data collected during a
defined reporting period. It demonstrates that the benefit-risk profile
of the device remains acceptable.

</p>

<div class="grid">

<div class="card">

<h3>Typical PSUR Contents</h3>

<ul>

<li>PMS Summary</li>

<li>Sales Data</li>

<li>Complaint Statistics</li>

<li>Trend Analysis</li>

<li>CAPA Summary</li>

<li>Benefit-Risk Evaluation</li>

<li>PMCF Findings</li>

<li>Conclusions</li>

</ul>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Inputs to PSUR</h3>

<ul>

<li>Complaint Database</li>

<li>Vigilance Reports</li>

<li>Literature Review</li>

<li>PMCF Activities</li>

<li>Risk Management File</li>

<li>Clinical Evaluation Report</li>

</ul>

</div>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Post Market Clinical Follow-up (PMCF)</h2>

<p>

PMCF is a continuous process of collecting clinical data after market
release to verify long-term safety and clinical performance.

PMCF findings are incorporated into the Clinical Evaluation Report (CER)
and Risk Management File (RMF).

</p>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Field Safety Corrective Action (FSCA)</h2>

<p>

An FSCA is an action taken by the manufacturer to reduce the risk of
death or serious deterioration in health associated with a medical
device already placed on the market.

</p>

<table>

<tr>
<th>Example</th>
<th>Action</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Incorrect IFU</td>
<td>Issue corrected Instructions for Use.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Packaging defect</td>
<td>Recall affected batches.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Software issue</td>
<td>Release validated software update.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Implant issue</td>
<td>Notify hospitals and regulatory authorities.</td>
</tr>

</table>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Orthopedic Implant PMS Example</h2>

<table>

<tr>
<th>Observed Issue</th>
<th>PMS Action</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Rasp mismatch</td>
<td>Complaint investigation and CAPA.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Trial implant mismatch</td>
<td>Risk assessment and IFU update.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Packaging damage</td>
<td>Packaging validation review.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Sterility complaint</td>
<td>Sterilization process investigation.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Instrument wear</td>
<td>Design review and supplier evaluation.</td>
</tr>

</table>

</div>

</section>
<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>PMS Report Structure</h2>

<p>

A Post Market Surveillance Report summarizes all post-market activities,
complaints, trend analysis, CAPA and regulatory actions. It demonstrates
that the medical device continues to meet safety and performance
requirements throughout its lifecycle.

</p>

<div class="grid">

<div class="card">

<h3>Typical PMS Report Contents</h3>

<ul>

<li>Product Description</li>

<li>Intended Purpose</li>

<li>Sales & Distribution Data</li>

<li>Complaint Summary</li>

<li>Incident Monitoring</li>

<li>Trend Analysis</li>

<li>CAPA Summary</li>

<li>PMCF Findings</li>

<li>Benefit-Risk Evaluation</li>

<li>Conclusions & Recommendations</li>

</ul>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Supporting Documents</h3>

<ul>

<li>Complaint Register</li>

<li>Risk Management File</li>

<li>Clinical Evaluation Report</li>

<li>Vigilance Reports</li>

<li>Recall Records</li>

<li>CAPA Records</li>

<li>Customer Feedback</li>

<li>Literature Review</li>

</ul>

</div>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Real Industry Case Study</h2>

<div class="card">

<h3>Orthopedic Hip Implant PMS</h3>

<p>

A manufacturer reviewed complaint data collected during the annual PMS
period.

No serious adverse events were reported.

Two customer complaints related to instrument compatibility were
received and investigated.

Trend analysis showed no increase in complaint frequency and no new
hazards were identified.

The Risk Management File and Clinical Evaluation Report were reviewed
and no changes to the benefit-risk profile were required.

</p>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Common Audit Questions</h2>

<div class="grid">

<div class="card">

<h3>Question 1</h3>

<p>

How is complaint data collected and evaluated?

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Question 2</h3>

<p>

How is trend analysis performed?

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Question 3</h3>

<p>

How is PMS linked with the Risk Management File?

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Question 4</h3>

<p>

When is a Vigilance Report required?

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Question 5</h3>

<p>

How are CAPA effectiveness checks performed?

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>Question 6</h3>

<p>

How often is the PMS Report updated?

</p>

</div>

</div>

</div>

</section>

<section>

<div class="container">

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="grid">

<div class="card">

<h3>What is PMS?</h3>

<p>

PMS is a continuous process of collecting and evaluating information
about a medical device after it has been placed on the market.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>What is the difference between PMS and PMCF?</h3>

<p>

PMS includes all post-market activities, while PMCF specifically focuses
on collecting additional clinical evidence after commercialization.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>What is PSUR?</h3>

<p>

The Periodic Safety Update Report summarizes PMS findings, benefit-risk
evaluation and post-market performance over a defined period.

</p>

</div>

<div class="card">

<h3>When should a Recall be initiated?</h3>

<p>

A recall should be considered when a device presents an unacceptable
risk to patients or users and corrective action is required.

</p>

</div>

</div>

</div>

</section>

